As anyone who shops at these supermarkets will know, there are a few major

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:02.819
differences between ALDI and Lidl and most traditional supermarket chains.

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:05.510
The first is the size.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:10.969
ALDI and Lidl tend to be smaller, with ALDIs in particular

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:14.909
being much smaller, typically around 1,000 metres squared.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:22.200
The selection of products on offer tends to be a lot smaller than traditional supermarkets, with

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:30.890
ALDI offering around 1,500 different items compared to around 31,000 in traditional supermarkets.

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:38.300
So instead of there being 5 or 10 different options for tomato ketchup, let’s

00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:43.790
say, with different brands and sizes of bottle, there might be just one or two.

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:49.380
And these products probably have names that sound a bit familiar to you,

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:54.619
they sound like brands that you have heard of, and the packaging is probably

00:06:54.679 --> 00:06:59.399
pretty similar, but you look more closely and the name is slightly different.

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:05.620
Walking around the supermarket you will probably notice that produce is stored in

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:11.710
the box in which it came, so there are no beautiful displays of apples or bananas,

00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:16.809
they are all still in the cardboard boxes in which they were packed, so you need

00:07:16.809 --> 00:07:21.479
to fish into the box to take out your fruit or vegetables or whatever it is.

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:26.809
Another difference is that you would probably struggle to find many employees

