Typically ALDI and Lidl are 15-20% cheaper than traditional

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:29.380
supermarkets, so there are considerable savings to be had.

00:08:30.490 --> 00:08:35.480
Now, you probably wouldn’t be surprised only when you see the final bill; as

00:08:35.480 --> 00:08:41.099
you might expect, ALDI and Lidl make the low prices of their items very visible

00:08:41.179 --> 00:08:45.850
throughout the supermarket, forever reminding you of the value you are getting.

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:51.840
In particular, they offer incredibly low prices on so-called “reference

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:57.870
goods” or “benchmark items”, in the UK that’s things like a pint of milk

00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:02.400
or a loaf of bread, products that people would typically know the price of.

00:09:03.549 --> 00:09:09.410
These goods are often sold at cost price, or even at a loss, because

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:14.310
their low price can easily be compared to other supermarkets, so you think

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:20.039
“oh, a pint of milk at ALDI is 90p, I paid £1.20 the other day at Tesco”.

00:09:20.759 --> 00:09:25.470
And when this happens, it reinforces the idea in a consumer’s mind that

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:30.180
everything in the supermarket is similarly cheap, which it normally is..

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:36.389
In terms of how they manage to make the products so much cheaper, well there

00:09:36.389 --> 00:09:41.380
are some things that you can see and some things that are less visible.

00:09:42.835 --> 00:09:47.720
Even with knowing little about how to run a supermarket, anyone who goes into

00:09:47.720 --> 00:09:53.258
one of their stores can see just by walking around how costs are being cut.

00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:59.620
Everything we talked about just a few minutes ago, from the fact that goods are left in boxes

00:09:59.629 --> 00:10:04.320
for the shopper to unpack themselves to the fact that there are very few staff members working

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:10.920
there, this is purposefully designed so that the cost savings are very visible to the customer.

00:10:12.397 --> 00:10:16.587
The point is that everything in an ALDI or Lidl reminds

00:10:16.597 --> 00:10:20.197
you, the customer, that the price is going to be low.

00:10:21.177 --> 00:10:26.567
And you don’t mind that there is a more limited choice of products or that it’s hard to find

00:10:26.567 --> 00:10:30.907
someone to tell you where the eggs are or that you have to remove a box to get to the tomatoes.

00:10:31.317 --> 00:10:36.017
You don’t mind doing it because you understand that you will pay less.

00:10:37.117 --> 00:10:43.057
It’s a very similar sort of idea as why the low-cost airline Ryanair plants

00:10:43.067 --> 00:10:47.937
stories in the press about how it might even charge people to use the toilet, or

00:10:48.117 --> 00:10:53.507
its social media teams jump on and embrace complaints about a lack of a good view.

00:10:54.247 --> 00:10:58.477
What they want people to remember is that the company has cut all

00:10:58.507 --> 00:11:03.777
possible costs, and is passing the savings on to you, as a consumer.

00:11:05.087 --> 00:11:10.047
And there are, of course, many cost saving mechanisms that are less visible.

00:11:11.037 --> 00:11:16.447
Because the supermarket chains are now so big and can order such large volumes,

00:11:16.727 --> 00:11:21.637
they can negotiate better prices with suppliers, which they pass on to consumers.

00:11:22.517 --> 00:11:25.627
The limited amount of products that they stock reduces

00:11:25.627 --> 00:11:28.617
complexity, thereby reducing operational costs.

00:11:29.397 --> 00:11:35.547
The fact that they have their own brand labels means they can reduce costs, and in some markets

00:11:35.737 --> 00:11:41.917
they only accepted payment in cash, not card, so they didn’t have to pay payment processing fees.

00:11:43.207 --> 00:11:47.187
And the end result of all of this cost cutting is that they can

00:11:47.187 --> 00:11:51.767
afford to offer the lowest prices and still make a healthy profit.

00:11:53.283 --> 00:11:58.287
In the case of both ALDI and Lidl, going right back to their humble beginnings,

00:11:58.847 --> 00:12:04.917
this has always been their strategy: deliver good quality products at a low price.

00:12:06.337 --> 00:12:13.527
ALDI is a little older than Lidl, tracing its roots back to 1946 to Lidl’s 1973.

00:12:14.537 --> 00:12:21.117
The story of ALDI is also more interesting, as it was founded by two brothers who then split

00:12:21.147 --> 00:12:27.207
the company into two after a row over whether the supermarket would sell cigarettes or not.

00:12:28.327 --> 00:12:31.547
One brother thought it was a good idea, the other was

00:12:31.547 --> 00:12:34.717
concerned about theft if they started to stock cigarettes.

00:12:35.537 --> 00:12:39.927
And instead of coming to some agreement, the pair decided

00:12:40.047 --> 00:12:43.907
to take the nuclear option; they split the company into two.

00:12:45.128 --> 00:12:51.307
And they did so along geographical lines, so there was ALDI Nord in the

00:12:51.317 --> 00:12:55.637
northern half of Germany and ALDI Süd in the southern half of Germany.

00:12:56.537 --> 00:13:01.327
Same name, slightly different logo, similar but ever so slightly

00:13:01.327 --> 00:13:05.577
different product range, and two completely separate businesses.

00:13:06.417 --> 00:13:13.267
It is a most unusual arrangement, but it seems to work, and the two rival companies have

00:13:13.267 --> 00:13:18.227
divided the world into different regions so they are not forced to compete with each other.

00:13:19.597 --> 00:13:24.667
And as to their global aspirations, in the late 1980s and early

00:13:24.667 --> 00:13:30.537
1990s both ALDI and Lidl started to expand beyond the German borders.

00:13:31.867 --> 00:13:36.687
The first ALDI store in the UK opened in Birmingham on the 5th of April,

00:13:36.687 --> 00:13:42.477
1990, and there are now more than 1,000 stores across the country, making

00:13:42.477 --> 00:13:47.267
the UK one of the most important markets outside its home market of Germany.

00:13:48.617 --> 00:13:54.077
Lidl arrived in the UK just a few years later, in 1996, and

00:13:54.287 --> 00:13:58.877
now has a similar amount of stores, 960 at the last count.

00:14:00.027 --> 00:14:05.457
And both of these supermarkets have now taken a sizable bite out of the business of

00:14:05.457 --> 00:14:11.087
the established British supermarkets, companies like Tesco, Sainsbury’s and ASDA.

00:14:12.407 --> 00:14:17.137
Today, ALDI and Lidl are the fifth and sixth most popular supermarkets

00:14:17.137 --> 00:14:21.704
in the country, accounting for 10% and 8% of the market respectively.

00:14:22.584 --> 00:14:26.414
It is a similar story in most of the other European markets in which they

00:14:26.414 --> 00:14:31.510
have a presence, although not to quite as extreme an extent as in the UK.

00:14:32.765 --> 00:14:34.514
It wasn’t all plain sailing though.

00:14:34.994 --> 00:14:39.574
It took a long time for ALDI and Lidl to really break through in the UK

00:14:39.574 --> 00:14:44.174
market, and they spent a vast amount of money trying to get it right.

00:14:45.604 --> 00:14:49.554
Initially they tried what had worked in Germany: competing

00:14:49.564 --> 00:14:53.894
on price alone, on a very limited selection of basic goods.

00:14:55.044 --> 00:14:59.964
While this strategy had worked with the notoriously price-sensitive German supermarket

00:14:59.964 --> 00:15:05.894
shopper, and worked with a particularly budget-conscious type of British consumer, to

00:15:05.894 --> 00:15:11.374
take a real chunk out of the British market, the German stores needed to attract the

00:15:11.384 --> 00:15:16.664
middle-class shopper who didn’t necessarily want to be seen in a bargain supermarket.

00:15:17.914 --> 00:15:21.624
And it was here that ALDI and Lidl did something

00:15:21.664 --> 00:15:25.114
clever to try to attract these more affluent consumers.

00:15:26.244 --> 00:15:29.344
They branched out into more premium items.

00:15:30.204 --> 00:15:36.144
From caviar to champagne to serrano ham, they started to stock a selection

00:15:36.354 --> 00:15:40.904
of so-called “premium” products at incredibly competitive prices.

00:15:42.354 --> 00:15:45.374
Soon enough, word started to spread.

00:15:46.614 --> 00:15:51.424
Whether it was a journalist or a forty-something business owner driving an Audi,

00:15:51.934 --> 00:15:56.844
people seemed to be pleasantly surprised by the quality of these premium products.

00:15:57.304 --> 00:16:01.144
It was something that they weren’t expecting, given the low price tag.

00:16:02.024 --> 00:16:08.214
Wines and champagne from ALDI have won awards, and their premium products tend

00:16:08.234 --> 00:16:14.114
to be rated as highly or higher than similar items from traditional supermarkets,

00:16:14.554 --> 00:16:20.064
or even from more premium supermarkets such as Waitrose or Marks & Spencer.

00:16:21.214 --> 00:16:27.904
Getting a bargain on a premium product at ALDI became a source of pride, a talking point

00:16:27.914 --> 00:16:33.894
for parents at the school gates, and looking at the BMWs and Mercedes parked in the

00:16:33.894 --> 00:16:39.994
car parks of Lidls and ALDIs, it is clear that they are doing a good job at attracting

00:16:39.994 --> 00:16:45.184
more affluent shoppers, people in search of premium products at a reasonable price.

00:16:45.984 --> 00:16:51.364
So, the German discount supermarkets had finally managed to achieve the impossible, to

00:16:51.364 --> 00:16:56.544
get affluent British shoppers to poke their noses inside and see what it was all about.

00:16:58.144 --> 00:17:03.524
And when these shoppers came through the doors, perhaps after reading in a newspaper about an

00:17:03.524 --> 00:17:09.094
award-winning French wine from ALDI or hearing from a friend that Lidl was selling Canadian

00:17:09.094 --> 00:17:16.404
lobsters for £4.99 a pop, they would be confronted with the magic of the supermarkets firsthand.

00:17:17.374 --> 00:17:21.964
Good quality products, overall, and very competitive prices.

00:17:22.614 --> 00:17:27.694
And lest I forget, there is another canny strategy that both stores

00:17:27.694 --> 00:17:32.024
operate to bring bargain hunters to the store, week after week.

00:17:33.094 --> 00:17:38.984
As you may know, they both have an aisle in the middle where they sell non-food items.

00:17:39.824 --> 00:17:43.344
To quote the Lidl website, “Cruise down our Middle of

00:17:43.344 --> 00:17:46.934
Lidl aisle for household kit you never knew you needed.”

00:17:48.387 --> 00:17:54.177
In this part of the supermarket, which ALDI calls Special Buys and Lidl calls

00:17:54.357 --> 00:17:59.337
the Middle of Lidl, the supermarkets sell a time-limited selection of general

00:17:59.337 --> 00:18:04.937
household stuff at very low prices, with new products being offered every week.

00:18:05.977 --> 00:18:10.667
So the idea is that it brings people back to the store in search of

00:18:10.667 --> 00:18:15.387
an amazing bargain on everything from frying pans to Christmas trees.

00:18:16.557 --> 00:18:22.677
When I was researching this episode, the main item on sale was a dog shade tent

00:18:22.957 --> 00:18:29.747
for the bargain price of £14.99, so I would imagine that, even for dog owners,

00:18:30.047 --> 00:18:34.617
that fits into the category of “household kit you never knew you needed”.

00:18:36.387 --> 00:18:42.997
This has, in the UK at least, become a cultural phenomenon of sorts, with online communities

00:18:43.167 --> 00:18:48.507
and social media groups dedicated to sharing and discussing the latest finds, and

00:18:48.517 --> 00:18:53.857
bringing people back into the shop, week after week, in the hope of snagging a bargain.

00:18:55.097 --> 00:18:59.387
All of this has combined to create a fearsome force.

00:19:00.017 --> 00:19:08.297
The discount retailers in the UK have an almost 20% market share, up from 0% thirty years ago.

00:19:09.297 --> 00:19:13.697
It is a similar story in the other markets in which ALDI and Lidl operate,

00:19:13.977 --> 00:19:18.927
although few have managed to catch up quite as fast as they have done in the UK.

00:19:20.067 --> 00:19:25.177
So, the story of these two German supermarkets is a fascinating one of

00:19:25.187 --> 00:19:30.267
national preferences, adapting to local tastes, and savvy business operations.

00:19:30.907 --> 00:19:34.877
And it reminds us about one fundamental human characteristic.

00:19:35.747 --> 00:19:40.667
For all of the differences and regional preferences, for all of the French’s commitment

00:19:40.667 --> 00:19:46.317
to quality and the Swedes’ dedication to environmental sustainability, from Paris to Pisa,

00:19:46.707 --> 00:19:53.727
Palmplona to Philadelphia, there is one thing that unites us all: nobody can resist a bargain.

